The SOLID principles are the "North Star" of object-oriented design. Introduced by Robert C. Martin (Uncle Bob), these five rules help developers move away from "fragile" code—where changing one thing breaks ten others—and toward systems that are easy to maintain, scale, and understand.
________________________________________
1. S: Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
"A class should have one, and only one, reason to change. Must have single functionality,  implementing multiple functionalities can mesh up the code"
In simple terms, a class should do one thing. If a class handles database logic, logging, and data processing all at once, it becomes "God Object" that is terrifying to modify.
•	The Problem: If you change the database schema, you might accidentally break the logging logic because they are intertwined.
•	The Goal: Keep classes small and focused.
________________________________________
2. O: Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
"Software entities should be open for extension, but closed for modification."
You should be able to add new functionality to a system without touching the existing, tested code.
•	The Problem: If you have an AreaCalculator that uses a bunch of if statements to check if a shape is a Circle or Square, you have to modify that class every time you add a new shape (like a Triangle).
•	The Goal: Use Interfaces or Abstract Classes. Instead of checking types, create a Shape interface with a calculateArea() method. Now, you can add as many new shapes as you want without ever changing the AreaCalculator.
________________________________________
3. L: Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
"Objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without breaking the application. Subclass methods must not violate the intension of parent class"
This is the most technical principle. It means a "child" class must truly be a version of its "parent."
•	The Problem: The classic "Square-Rectangle" problem. A Square is mathematically a Rectangle, but if your Rectangle class has setWidth() and setHeight() independently, and your Square class forces them to be equal, substituting a Square where a Rectangle is expected will cause bugs.
•	The Goal: Ensure subclasses follow the "contract" of the parent. If a child class can't do what the parent does, it probably shouldn't inherit from it.
________________________________________
4. I: Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
"No client should be forced to depend on methods it does not use."
Larger interfaces should be split into smaller ones
Basically, don't create "fat" interfaces.
•	The Problem: Imagine an interface IMachine with print(), scan(), and fax(). If you have an old printer that can't scan, you still have to implement the scan() method (usually leaving it empty or throwing an error). This is "polluted" code.
•	The Goal: Split large interfaces into smaller, more specific ones (e.g., IPrinter, IScanner).
________________________________________
5. D: Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
"Depend on abstractions, not on concretions."
High-level modules (the "brains" of your app) should not depend on low-level modules (the "tools" like databases or APIs). Both should depend on interfaces.
•	The Problem: If your Store class directly creates an instance of PayPalPayment, your store is now "hardcoded" to PayPal. Switching to Stripe would require rewriting the Store class.
•	The Goal: The Store should depend on a generic IPaymentProcessor. You "inject" whatever specific payment tool you want at runtime.
________________________________________
Why should you care?
Following SOLID doesn't just make you look like a pro; it saves your "future self" from a headache. It leads to:
1.	Easier Testing: Small, decoupled classes are a dream to unit test.
2.	Lower Technical Debt: You won't be afraid to change your code.
3.	Better Teamwork: Different developers can work on different components without stepping on each other's toes.
