Think of Design Patterns as "blueprints" for solving recurring problems in software design. They aren't finished pieces of code that you can copy-paste; rather, they are templates for how to structure your objects and classes to make your code more flexible, reusable, and maintainable.
These patterns were popularized by the "Gang of Four" (GoF) in 1994 and are generally categorized into three main groups based on their purpose.

In software engineering, Creational Patterns are design patterns that deal with object creation mechanisms. Instead of instantiating objects directly (which can hard-code specific complexities into your program), these patterns provide a way to create objects while hiding the creation logic.
The goal is to decouple a system from how its objects are created, composed, and represented. This makes your code more flexible, reusable, and easier to maintain as it grows.
________________________________________
1. Singleton Pattern
The Singleton pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it. It is commonly used for shared resources like database connections, thread pools, or configuration settings.
Key Characteristics:
•	Private Constructor: Prevents other classes from instantiating it.
•	Static Instance: Holds the single instance of the class.
•	Static Access Method: A public method (usually getInstance()) that returns the instance.
Example Code (Java):
Java
public class DatabaseConnection {
    private static DatabaseConnection instance;

    // Private constructor
    private DatabaseConnection() {
        System.out.println("Connecting to Database...");
    }

    // Static method to get the single instance
    public static DatabaseConnection getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new DatabaseConnection();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
________________________________________
2. Factory Method Pattern
The Factory Method pattern provides an interface for creating objects in a superclass but allows subclasses to alter the type of objects that will be created. It promotes "loose coupling" by eliminating the need to bind application-specific classes into the code.
Key Characteristics:
•	Product Interface: Defines the interface of objects the factory method creates.
•	Concrete Products: Different implementations of the product interface.
•	Creator: Declares the factory method.
Example Code (Python):
// 1. Product Interface
interface Shape {
    void draw();
}

// 2. Concrete Product: Circle
class Circle implements Shape {
    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Circle");
    }
}

// 3. Concrete Product: Square
class Square implements Shape {
    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Square");
    }
}

// 4. Factory Class
class ShapeFactory {
    // Use getShape method to get object of type shape 
    public static Shape getShape(String shapeType) {
        if (shapeType == null) {
            return null;
        }
        
        // Using ignoreCase to make the factory more robust
        if (shapeType.equalsIgnoreCase("CIRCLE")) {
            return new Circle();
        } else if (shapeType.equalsIgnoreCase("SQUARE")) {
            return new Square();
        }
        
        return null;
    }
}

// 5. Usage
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Get an object of Circle and call its draw method.
        Shape shape1 = ShapeFactory.getShape("CIRCLE");
        if (shape1 != null) {
            shape1.draw(); // Output: Drawing a Circle
        }

        // Get an object of Square and call its draw method.
        Shape shape2 = ShapeFactory.getShape("SQUARE");
        if (shape2 != null) {
            shape2.draw(); // Output: Drawing a Square
        }
    }
}________________________________________
3. Builder Pattern
The Builder pattern is used to construct complex objects step by step. Unlike other creational patterns, Builder doesn't require products to have a common interface. This is especially useful when an object has many optional parameters or a complicated initialization process.
Key Characteristics:
•	Builder: Interface for creating parts of a Product object.
•	Concrete Builder: Implements the Builder interface and keeps track of the product it creates.
•	Director: Manages the construction process using a Builder object.
•	Product: The complex object being built.
Example Code (JavaScript):
JavaScript
class Pizza {
    constructor() {
        this.size = "";
        this.cheese = false;
        this.pepperoni = false;
    }
}

class PizzaBuilder {
    constructor() {
        this.pizza = new Pizza();
    }

    setSize(size) {
        this.pizza.size = size;
        return this; // Return 'this' for chaining
    }

    addCheese() {
        this.pizza.cheese = true;
        return this;
    }

    addPepperoni() {
        this.pizza.pepperoni = true;
        return this;
    }

    build() {
        return this.pizza;
    }
}

// Usage
const myPizza = new PizzaBuilder()
                    .setSize("Large")
                    .addCheese()
                    .addPepperoni()
                    .build();

console.log(myPizza);
________________________________________
Comparison Summary
Pattern	Best Used When...	Key Benefit
Singleton	You need exactly one instance of a class.	Shared state/resource control.
Factory	You don't know the exact types and dependencies of objects beforehand.	Decouples creation from usage.
Builder	You need to create an object with many optional parts or configurations.	Improved readability and "step-by-step" control.


While Creational patterns focus on how objects are born, Structural Patterns focus on how classes and objects are composed to form larger, more flexible structures. They use inheritance or composition to allow different parts of a system to work together seamlessly without being tightly coupled.
Think of it as the "architecture" of your objects—ensuring that if one part of the system changes, the rest doesn't come crashing down.
________________________________________
1. Adapter Pattern
The Adapter acts as a bridge between two incompatible interfaces. It wraps an existing class with a new interface so that it becomes compatible with a client's expectation. It’s often compared to a physical power adapter that lets a US plug fit into a European socket.
Key Characteristics:
•	Target: The domain-specific interface the client uses.
•	Adaptee: The existing interface that needs adapting.
•	Adapter: The class that implements the Target and wraps the Adaptee.
Java Example:
Imagine you have a Movable interface that returns speed in Miles per Hour, but your new system requires Kilometers per Hour.
Java
// Target Interface
interface Movable {
    double getSpeed(); // Returns speed in MPH
}

// Adaptee (The class we want to adapt)
class AstonMartin implements Movable {
    @Override
    public double getSpeed() {
        return 220.0; 
    }
}

// Adapter Interface
interface MovableAdapter {
    double getSpeed(); // Should return speed in KPH
}

// Concrete Adapter
class MovableAdapterImpl implements MovableAdapter {
    private Movable luxuryCars;

    public MovableAdapterImpl(Movable car) {
        this.luxuryCars = car;
    }

    @Override
    public double getSpeed() {
        return convertMPHtoKPH(luxuryCars.getSpeed());
    }

    private double convertMPHtoKPH(double mph) {
        return mph * 1.60934;
    }
}
________________________________________
2. Facade Pattern
The Facade pattern provides a simplified interface to a complex library, framework, or any other complex set of classes. It hides the "mess" of the inner workings and provides a single entry point for the client.
Key Characteristics:
•	Simplicity: Reduces the learning curve for a complex subsystem.
•	Decoupling: The client doesn't need to know about the 10 different classes running in the background.
Java Example:
Think of a Home Theater system. To watch a movie, you have to turn on the lights, the DVD player, the projector, and the speakers. A Facade handles all of that with one method.
Java
class SoundSystem { public void on() { System.out.println("Sound on"); } }
class Projector { public void on() { System.out.println("Projector on"); } }

// Facade
class HomeTheaterFacade {
    private SoundSystem sound;
    private Projector projector;

    public HomeTheaterFacade(SoundSystem s, Projector p) {
        this.sound = s;
        this.projector = p;
    }

    public void watchMovie() {
        System.out.println("Get ready to watch a movie...");
        sound.on();
        projector.on();
    }
}

// Usage
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HomeTheaterFacade theater = new HomeTheaterFacade(new SoundSystem(), new Projector());
        theater.watchMovie(); 
    }
}
________________________________________
3. Proxy Pattern
The Proxy pattern provides a placeholder or representative for another object to control access to it. It acts as an intermediary, often used for lazy loading (creating expensive objects only when needed), logging, or security/access control.
Key Characteristics:
•	Remote Proxy: Represents an object in a different address space.
•	Virtual Proxy: Handles "expensive" objects by delaying creation.
•	Protection Proxy: Checks access rights before allowing a call.
Java Example:
Using a Proxy to load a high-resolution image only when the user actually calls display().
Java
interface Image {
    void display();
}

class RealImage implements Image {
    private String filename;

    public RealImage(String filename) {
        this.filename = filename;
        loadFromDisk(); // Expensive operation
    }

    private void loadFromDisk() {
        System.out.println("Loading " + filename);
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Displaying " + filename);
    }
}

// Proxy
class ProxyImage implements Image {
    private RealImage realImage;
    private String filename;

    public ProxyImage(String filename) {
        this.filename = filename;
    }

    @Override
    public void display() {
        if (realImage == null) {
            realImage = new RealImage(filename); // Lazy loading
        }
        realImage.display();
    }
}
________________________________________
Comparison Summary
Pattern	Primary Purpose	Real-world Analogy
Adapter	Fixes incompatible interfaces.	Power plug adapter.
Facade	Simplifies a complex subsystem.	A single "On" button for a theater.
Proxy	Controls access to an object.	A bank check representing cash.























1. Creational Patterns
Focus: How objects are created. These patterns hide the logic of how objects are instantiated, so your system doesn't depend on how objects are created or composed.
•	Singleton: Ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it (e.g., a single Database Connection pool).
•	Factory Method: Provides an interface for creating objects but allows subclasses to alter the type of objects that will be created.
•	Abstract Factory: Lets you produce families of related objects without specifying their concrete classes (e.g., a UI kit that creates "Dark Mode" buttons and checkboxes together).
•	Builder: Used for constructing complex objects step-by-step (e.g., an HTML builder or a Custom Pizza order).
•	Prototype: Allows cloning existing objects without making your code dependent on their classes.
________________________________________
2. Structural Patterns
Focus: How classes and objects are composed to form larger structures. These patterns ensure that if one part of a system changes, the entire structure doesn't need to change.
•	Adapter: Acts as a wrapper between two incompatible interfaces. Think of it like a power plug adapter for traveling abroad.
•	Decorator: Allows you to "stack" behaviors onto an object dynamically without changing its original code (e.g., adding "Milk" and "Sugar" wrappers to a basic "Coffee" object).
•	Facade: Provides a simplified interface to a complex library or subsystem. Instead of managing 10 different classes, you talk to one "Facade" class.
•	Proxy: Provides a placeholder for another object to control access to it (e.g., a "Lazy Loading" proxy that only loads a heavy image when it’s actually needed).
•	Composite: Lets you treat individual objects and compositions of objects uniformly (e.g., a folder system where a "File" and a "Folder" are handled the same way).
________________________________________
3. Behavioral Patterns
Focus: How objects communicate and assign responsibilities. These patterns are concerned with the algorithms and the assignment of responsibilities between objects.
•	Observer: A "subscription" mechanism. When one object changes state, all its subscribers are notified automatically (e.g., a "Notify Me" button on an e-commerce site).
•	Strategy: Defines a family of algorithms and makes them interchangeable at runtime. For example, a Navigation app switching between "Walking," "Driving," and "Cycling" routes.
•	Command: Turns a request into a stand-alone object. This allows for features like "Undo/Redo" because every action is saved as a Command object.
•	State: Allows an object to alter its behavior when its internal state changes (e.g., a Document object behaving differently in "Draft," "Moderation," and "Published" modes).
•	Chain of Responsibility: Passes a request along a chain of handlers. Each handler decides either to process the request or pass it to the next handler (e.g., Middlewares in web development).
________________________________________
Why use Design Patterns?
•	Common Vocabulary: Instead of explaining a complex communication logic, you can just say, "We’re using the Observer pattern," and other developers will immediately understand the architecture.
•	Proven Solutions: These patterns have been stress-tested over decades. Using them helps you avoid the "hidden" bugs that come with custom, ad-hoc architectures.
•	Easy Refactoring: Because patterns promote decoupling (objects not being too "sticky" to each other), it's much easier to swap out parts of your system later.
