Creational Design Patterns: The "Architects" of Object Creation
In software engineering, the way you create objects can often lead to "tight coupling"—where classes are so dependent on each other that changing one breaks everything else. Creational Design Patterns solve this by separating the logic of creation from the logic of the system.
Instead of hardcoding a new ClassName(), these patterns provide a more flexible way to decide which objects to create, how to create them, and when.
________________________________________
1. Singleton Pattern
The Goal: Ensure a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it.
•	How it works: The class makes its constructor private and provides a static method (usually getInstance()) that returns the single instance.
•	Real-World Analogy: A government. There can be only one official government for a country. No matter who you are, when you "access" the government, you're interacting with the same entity.
•	Best For: Database connections, logging services, or configuration settings where having multiple instances would cause data inconsistency or waste memory.
________________________________________
2. Factory Method Pattern
The Goal: Define an interface for creating an object, but let subclasses decide which class to instantiate.
•	How it works: A "Creator" class defines a method for creating an object. Different "Concrete Creators" override this method to return different types of products.
•	Real-World Analogy: A logistics app. A Transport factory might have a createTransport() method. A RoadLogistics subclass will return a Truck object, while SeaLogistics returns a Ship object.
•	Best For: When your code doesn't know the exact types and dependencies of the objects it should work with beforehand.
________________________________________
3. Abstract Factory Pattern
The Goal: Provide an interface for creating families of related or dependent objects without specifying their concrete classes.
•	How it works: It’s like a "Factory of Factories." You define an interface for creating a set of products (e.g., createButton(), createCheckbox()).
•	Real-World Analogy: A furniture factory. A "Victorian" factory produces a Victorian Chair and a Victorian Sofa. A "Modern" factory produces a Modern Chair and a Modern Sofa. You don't mix a modern chair with a Victorian sofa.
•	Best For: When a system should be independent of how its products are created, and you need to ensure that the products you use together are compatible.
________________________________________
4. Builder Pattern
The Goal: Construct a complex object step-by-step. It allows you to produce different types and representations of an object using the same construction code.
•	How it works: Instead of a giant constructor with 10 parameters (some of which might be null), you use a "Builder" object. You call setA().setB().setC().build().
•	Real-World Analogy: Ordering a custom pizza. You start with the dough, then add sauce, then choose toppings. You don't get a "Standard Pizza" and then remove what you don't want; you build it from scratch.
•	Best For: Objects that require a lot of configuration or have many optional fields (like a User Profile or a complex SQL Query builder).
________________________________________
5. Prototype Pattern
The Goal: Create new objects by cloning an existing object (the prototype) instead of creating them from scratch.
•	How it works: The object itself implements a clone() method. When you need a copy, you ask the object to duplicate itself.
•	Real-World Analogy: Mitosis in cells. A cell doesn't get "built" by an external factory; it simply splits and copies its own state to create a new, identical cell.
•	Best For: When the cost of creating a new object is expensive (e.g., it involves a heavy database hit) and you already have a similar object in memory.
________________________________________
Summary Table: Which one to use?
Pattern	Focus	Use when...
Singleton	Uniqueness	You need exactly one instance of a class.
Factory Method	Subclasses	You want to delegate object creation to subclasses.
Abstract Factory	Families	You need to create groups of related objects.
Builder	Step-by-Step	You have a complex object with many optional parts.
Prototype	Cloning	You want to copy an existing object's state exactly.
