Structural Design Patterns: The "Connectors" of Software
Structural design patterns focus on how classes and objects are composed to form larger, more complex structures. They ensure that if one part of a system changes, the entire structure doesn't collapse. Essentially, they help you realize relationships between entities.
________________________________________
1. Adapter Pattern
The Goal: Allow incompatible interfaces to work together. It acts as a bridge between two objects.
•	How it works: You create an "Adapter" class that wraps an existing class. The adapter implements the interface the client expects and translates calls into a format the wrapped object understands.
•	Real-World Analogy: A travel power adapter. Your laptop has a three-prong plug, but the wall outlet in Europe only accepts two round pins. The adapter doesn't change the laptop or the wall; it just sits in the middle so they can communicate.
•	Best For: Integrating a third-party library or a legacy system whose interface doesn't match your current application’s code.
________________________________________
2. Decorator Pattern
The Goal: Attach new behaviors to objects dynamically by placing them inside special wrapper objects.
•	How it works: Instead of using inheritance (which is static), you wrap your object in a "Decorator" class. Both the object and the decorator share the same interface, so you can stack multiple decorators on top of each other.
•	Real-World Analogy: Dressing in layers. You are the "base object." When it’s cold, you put on a sweater (Decorator 1). If it rains, you put on a raincoat (Decorator 2). You still function as a "person," but you've gained new "warmth" and "waterproof" properties.
•	Best For: When you want to add features to an object at runtime without affecting other objects of the same class.
________________________________________
3. Facade Pattern
The Goal: Provide a simplified interface to a complex set of classes, a framework, or a library.
•	How it works: A "Facade" class provides a single, simple method that triggers a long chain of complex actions in the background. It hides the "mess" of the subsystem from the user.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Computer Power Button. When you press "Power," a dozen things happen (BIOS check, OS loading, hardware initialization). You don't care about those steps; you just want a single button to start the system.
•	Best For: Reducing dependencies between a client and a complex subsystem. It makes your API much easier to use.
________________________________________
4. Proxy Pattern
The Goal: Provide a substitute or placeholder for another object to control access to it.
•	How it works: A Proxy object sits in front of a "Real Subject." When a request comes in, the Proxy can perform tasks like checking permissions, logging, or "Lazy Loading" (only creating the real object when it's actually needed) before passing the request along.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Credit Card. The card is a proxy for your bank account. It represents the money, but when you buy something, the "Proxy" (card) handles the authorization before the "Real Subject" (your actual cash) is moved.
•	Best For: Adding security layers, caching results, or managing "expensive" objects that take up a lot of memory.
________________________________________
5. Composite Pattern
The Goal: Compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies. It lets clients treat individual objects and compositions of objects uniformly.
•	How it works: You have "Leaf" objects (the smallest unit) and "Composite" objects (containers that hold Leaves or other Composites). Both implement the same interface.
•	Real-World Analogy: A File System. A folder can contain files (Leaves) or other folders (Composites). When you ask for the "Size" of a folder, it calculates the size of everything inside it, treating the folder and the files the same way.
•	Best For: When you need to implement a tree-like structure, such as a UI component tree or an organizational chart.
________________________________________
6. Bridge Pattern
The Goal: Split a large class or a set of closely related classes into two separate hierarchies—Abstraction and Implementation—which can be developed independently.
•	How it works: Instead of a complex inheritance tree, you "bridge" the two. For example, instead of classes like RedCircle, BlueCircle, RedSquare, and BlueSquare, you have a Shape class that holds a reference to a Color interface.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Remote Control and a TV. The remote (Abstraction) has the logic for "Change Channel." The TV (Implementation) has the hardware to actually do it. You can upgrade the TV without needing a new remote, and vice versa.
________________________________________
7. Flyweight Pattern
The Goal: Save memory by sharing common parts of state between multiple objects instead of keeping all data in each object.
•	How it works: You separate an object's state into "Intrinsic" (constant data shared by many) and "Extrinsic" (unique data). You store the intrinsic state once and reference it.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Video Game with 1,000 Trees. Instead of storing the 3D model and texture data for every single tree, you store the model once and just record the 1,000 unique coordinates where the trees should appear.
________________________________________
Comparison: Structural Patterns at a Glance
Pattern	Key Utility
Adapter	Converts one interface to another.
Decorator	Adds responsibilities dynamically.
Facade	Simplifies a complex subsystem.
Proxy	Controls access to an object.
Composite	Treats groups of objects as a single object.
Bridge	Decouples an abstraction from its implementation.
Flyweight	Shares state to reduce memory usage.
