Behavioral Design Patterns: The "Communicators" of Software
While Creational patterns handle object creation and Structural patterns handle object relationships, Behavioral Design Patterns are all about communication. They define how objects talk to each other, how they distribute work, and how they manage complex control flows.
Think of them as the "social rules" for your objects.
________________________________________
1. Observer Pattern
The Goal: Create a subscription mechanism to notify multiple objects about any events that happen to the object they’re observing.
•	How it works: An "Observable" (or Subject) maintains a list of "Observers." When the state of the Subject changes, it automatically calls a notification method on all its Observers.
•	Real-World Analogy: A YouTube Channel. You are the "Observer" and the channel is the "Subject." When the channel uploads a new video, every subscriber receives a notification.
•	Best For: Implementing event-driven systems, such as a UI that needs to update when data changes.
________________________________________
2. Strategy Pattern
The Goal: Define a family of algorithms, put each of them into a separate class, and make their objects interchangeable.
•	How it works: Instead of a giant if/else block inside a method, you create an interface (e.g., PaymentStrategy). You then create concrete classes for each algorithm (e.g., CreditCardStrategy, BitcoinStrategy). The main class simply calls the strategy it's currently holding.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Navigation App. You want to get from Point A to Point B. You can choose to "Walk," "Drive," or "Bike." The app uses the same map but swaps the "Routing Strategy" based on your choice.
•	Best For: When you have many variations of an algorithm and want to switch between them at runtime.
________________________________________
3. Command Pattern
The Goal: Turn a request or action into a stand-alone object that contains all information about the request.
•	How it works: You wrap a call into a "Command" object. This allows you to pass the request as a method argument, delay its execution, or put it in a queue.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Restaurant Order. The waiter takes your "Order" (the Command) on a slip of paper. That slip contains all the info the chef needs. The waiter doesn't need to know how to cook; they just pass the Command to the Kitchen.
•	Best For: Implementing "Undo/Redo" functionality or task scheduling.
________________________________________
4. State Pattern
The Goal: Let an object alter its behavior when its internal state changes. The object will appear to change its class.
•	How it works: You extract state-specific behaviors into separate classes. The main object (Context) delegates the work to the "Current State" object.
•	Real-World Analogy: A Vending Machine. If the state is NoMoney, pressing the "Dispense" button does nothing. If the state is HasMoney, the same button release a snack and changes the state back to NoMoney.
•	Best For: Managing complex "State Machines" where behavior depends heavily on the current status.
________________________________________
5. Chain of Responsibility Pattern
The Goal: Pass requests along a chain of handlers. Upon receiving a request, each handler decides either to process the request or to pass it to the next handler in the chain.
•	How it works: Each handler has a reference to the "Next" handler. If Handler A can't solve the problem, it hands it off to Handler B.
•	Real-World Analogy: Tech Support. You call a Tier 1 agent. If they can't fix your router, they pass you to Tier 2. If Tier 2 can't fix it, they pass you to a Senior Engineer.
•	Best For: Middleware in web servers or multi-level validation logic.
________________________________________
6. Template Method Pattern
The Goal: Define the skeleton of an algorithm in a superclass but let subclasses override specific steps of the algorithm without changing its structure.
•	How it works: The parent class defines a "final" method that calls several other methods in a specific order. Subclasses implement the individual steps but cannot change the order of execution.
•	Real-World Analogy: Building a House. The "Template" is: 1. Build Foundation, 2. Build Walls, 3. Add Roof. You can choose "Brick Walls" or "Wood Walls," but you can't put the roof on before the foundation.
________________________________________
7. Memento Pattern
The Goal: Capture and externalize an object's internal state so that the object can be restored to this state later (without violating encapsulation).
•	How it works: The object (Originator) creates a "snapshot" of itself (Memento). A "Caretaker" keeps track of these snapshots.
•	Real-World Analogy: Save Points in a Video Game. You save your progress before a boss fight. If you lose, you "restore" your character to the exact state they were in at that save point.
